Why do we need operator overloading?
C++ was designed so that user-defined types (classes) can behave like built-in types (int, float).
Operator overloading helps achieve this by allowing operators like +, -, [], <<, etc. to work with objects.

🚀 Real-World Use Cases
1. 🧮 Mathematical Systems (Complex Numbers / Vectors)
c3 = c1 + c2;
v3 = v1 + v2;

Operator overloading is used to make user-defined classes behave like built-in types.

It improves code readability and allows natural expression of operations like +, -, <<, [], etc. on objects.

It is widely used in STL (vectors, iterators), smart pointers, math libraries, and stream I/O systems.

Operator overloading = making objects behave like primitive types.






=========================================================
C++ OPERATOR OVERLOADING – QUICK REVISION NOTES
=========================================================

========================
1. BASIC IDEA
========================
- Gives special meaning to operators for user-defined types.
- Example:
    obj1 + obj2
  becomes:
    obj1.operator+(obj2)

- It is Compile-Time Polymorphism.

========================
2. GENERAL SYNTAX
========================
return_type operator op (parameters)
{
    // logic
}

Example:
Complex operator+(Complex obj);

========================
3. COMMON INTERVIEW OVERLOADS
========================

STREAM OPERATORS (MOST IMPORTANT)
----------------------------------
cout << obj   → operator<<(cout, obj)
cin  >> obj   → operator>>(cin, obj)

Must be FRIEND functions.

----------------------------------
SUBSCRIPT
----------------------------------
obj[i] → operator[](i)

Must be MEMBER function.

----------------------------------
FUNCTION CALL
----------------------------------
obj() → operator()(args)

Used for Functors.

----------------------------------
INCREMENT/DECREMENT
----------------------------------
++obj  → operator++()
obj++  → operator++(int)

----------------------------------
DEREFERENCE / POINTER
----------------------------------
*obj   → operator*()
obj->  → operator->()

Used in Smart Pointers.

----------------------------------
NEW / DELETE
----------------------------------
Overload memory allocation:
operator new
operator delete

========================
4. KEY RULES (VERY IMPORTANT)
========================

✔ Must be member functions:
   - operator[]
   - operator()
   - operator=

✔ Usually friend functions:
   - operator<<
   - operator>>

✔ Cannot be overloaded:
   - .
   - ::
   - ?:
   - sizeof
   - typeid

========================
5. IMPORTANT CONCEPTS
========================

✔ Pre-increment:
   return reference (obj&)

✔ Post-increment:
   takes dummy int parameter

✔ operator* returns reference for chaining

✔ operator-> returns pointer to object

✔ return type often reference to support chaining

========================
6. MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
========================

Q. Why operator overloading?
A. To make user-defined types behave like built-in types.

Q. Why friend functions for << and >>?
A. Left operand is stream object (cannot modify std classes).

Q. Difference between pre and post ++?
A. Pre returns updated object, post returns old value.

Q. What is functor?
A. Class with operator() overloaded.

Q. Why operator new/delete are static?
A. No object exists during allocation/deallocation.

========================
7. KEY COMPILER CONVERSIONS
========================

obj + obj2     → obj.operator+(obj2)
obj[i]         → obj.operator[](i)
obj()          → obj.operator()()
obj++          → obj.operator++(0)
++obj          → obj.operator++()
cout << obj    → operator<<(cout, obj)
cin >> obj     → operator>>(cin, obj)

